# Commit message on code changes

When you **modify, create, or delete** project files during a query, end your response with a **Suggested commit message** section — even if the user did not ask you to commit.

## When to include it

- **Include** when you changed any source, config, test, migration, or asset files.
- **Skip** when the query was read-only (questions, reviews, explanations) and no files were changed.

## Format

Place the section at the **end** of the response, after your summary:

```markdown
## Suggested commit message

\`\`\`
<type>: <short subject in imperative mood>

<Optional 1–2 sentence body explaining why, not a file list.>
\`\`\`
```

## Message style

- Use conventional types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`, `ci`, `build`.
- Subject line: imperative, ≤72 characters, no trailing period.
- Body (optional): focus on **why**, not a bullet list of every file touched.
- Do **not** run `git commit` unless the user explicitly asks.

## Example

After adding a rate-limit middleware and test:

```markdown
## Suggested commit message

\`\`\`
feat: add rate limiting to login endpoint

Throttle failed login attempts to reduce brute-force risk.
\`\`\`
```
